Assignment 02 - Data Viz and Wrangling

Data Wrangling

You will need to download two datasets from https://github.com/USCbiostats/data-science-data. The individual and regional CHS datasets in 01_chs. The individual data includes personal and health characteristics of children in 12 communities across Southern California. The regional data include air quality measurements at the community level. Once downloaded, you can merge these datasets using the location variable. Once combined, you will need to do the following:

chs_individual <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/USCbiostats/data-science-data/master/01_chs/chs_individual.csv")

 x = chs_individual,
 y = chs_regional,
 by = "townname")

  1. After merging the data, make sure you donât have any duplicates by counting the number of rows. Make sure it matches.

    In the case of missing values, impute data using the average amongst individuals with the same values for the âmaleâ and âhispanicâ variables. For categorical variables, take the mode. If you are interested (and feel adventurous) in the theme of Data Imputation, take a look at this paper on âMultiple Imputationâ using the Amelia R package here.

  group_by(male, hispanic) %>%
  mutate_if(is.numeric, function(x) ifelse(is.na(x), mean(x, na.rm = TRUE), x))

mode <- function(x) {
  ux <- unique(x)
  ux[which.max(tabulate(match(x, ux)))]}
  1. Create a new categorical variable named âobesity_levelâ using the BMI measurement (underweight BMI<14; normal BMI 14-22; overweight BMI 22-24; obese BMI>24). To make sure the variable is rightly coded, create a summary table that contains the minimum BMI, maximum BMI, and the total number of observations per category.
chs <- chs %>%
    mutate(obesity_level = case_when(
    bmi < 14 ~ "underweight",
    bmi >= 14 & bmi <= 22 ~ "normal",
    bmi > 22 & bmi <= 24 ~ "overweight",
    bmi > 24 ~ "obese"))

summary_bmi <- chs %>%
  group_by(obesity_level) %>%
  summarize(
    min_bmi = min(bmi),
    max_bmi = max(bmi),
    total_obs = n())

print(summary_bmi)

  1. Create another categorical variable named âsmoke_gas_exposureâ that summarizes âSecond Hand Smokeâ and âGas Stove.â The variable should have four categories in total.
chs <- chs %>%
    mutate(smoke_gas_exposure = case_when(
    smoke == 0 & gasstove == 0 ~ "no_exposure",
    smoke == 1 & gasstove == 1 ~ "smoke_only",
    smoke == 0 & gasstove == 1 ~ "gas_only",
    smoke == 1 & gasstove == 1 ~ "both_exposures"))
  1. Create four summary tables showing the average (or proportion, if binary) and sd of âForced expiratory volume in 1 second (ml)â (an asthma indicator) by town, sex, obesity level, and âsmoke_gas_exposure.â
summary_town <- chs %>%
  group_by(townname) %>%
  summarize(
    avg_fev = mean(fev, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_fev = sd(fev,na.rm = TRUE))

Looking at the Data (EDA)

The primary questions of interest are:

  1. What is the association between BMI and FEV (forced expiratory volume)?

  2. What is the association between smoke and gas exposure and FEV?

  3. What is the association between PM2.5 exposure and FEV?

Follow the EDA checklist from week 3 and the previous assignment. Be sure to focus on the key variables.

  • Read in the data - done

plot(chs$bmi, chs$fev, pch=10, cex=0.2)

Visualization

Create the following figures and interpret them. Be sure to include easily understandable axes, titles, and legends.

  1. Facet plot showing scatterplots with regression lines of BMI vs FEV by âtownnameâ.
ggplot(data = chs) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = bmi, y = fev, color = townname)) +
  facet_wrap(~ townname, nrow = 1) +
  labs(
    title = "BMI vs. FEV by Town",
    x = "BMI",
    y = "FEV",
    color = "Town")
